    "markdown": "---\ntitle: \"Problem Set 1\"\nsubtitle: \"Current Population Survey (CPS) 2024\"\nauthor: \"Andrea Recine\"\ndate: today\nlang: en\n\nformat:\n  html:\n    # Layout\n    theme: flatly\n    toc: true\n    toc-depth: 3\n    toc-title: \"Contents\"\n    toc-location: right       \n    number-sections: true\n    \n    # Code\n    code-fold: false\n    code-tools: true\n    code-copy: true\n    code-block-bg: true\n    code-block-border-left: false\n    highlight-style: github\n    \n    # Output\n    embed-resources: true\n    \n    # Typography\n    fontsize: 1.1em\n    linestretch: 1.6\n\nexecute:\n  warning: false\n  message: false\n  echo: true\n\nknitr:\n  opts_chunk:\n    comment: \"#>\"\n    fig.align: \"center\"\n    fig.width: 7\n    fig.height: 4.5\n\n---\n\n## Introduction\n\n### Dati\n\nI data utilizzati in questa tutorial come froml **Current Population  Survey Annual Social and Economic Supplement (CPS-ASEC)** per l'anno 2024, estratti tramite IPUMS CPS [Flood et al., 2025]. Il sample utilizzato è una sottoselezione di 2000 observations di lavoratori in età lavorativa (16-65 anni) con redditi da lavoro positivi.\n\nI microdata IPUMS sono soggetti a licenza d'uso e non vengono ridistribuiti. Studenti interessati a replicare le analisi possono registrarsi gratuitamente su <https://cps.ipums.org/> e scaricare un estratto analogo.\n\n**Citazione completa**:\n\n> Sarah Flood, Miriam King, Renae Rodgers, Steven Ruggles, J. Robert Warren, \n> Daniel Backman, Etienne Breton, Grace Cooper, Julia A. Rivera Drew, \n> Stephanie Richards, David Van Riper, and Kari C.W. Williams. *IPUMS CPS: \n> Version 13.0* [dataset]. Minneapolis, MN: IPUMS, 2025. \n> <https://doi.org/10.18128/D030.V13.0>\n\n\n\n::: {.cell layout-align=\"center\"}\n\n```{.r .cell-code}\nlibrary(tidyverse)\nlibrary(knitr)\nlibrary(tinytable)\nlibrary(modelsummary)\nlibrary(fixest)\n```\n:::\n\n\n\n\n::: {.cell layout-align=\"center\"}\n\n```{.r .cell-code}\nlibrary(wooldridge)\n```\n:::\n\n\n\n::: {.cell layout-align=\"center\"}\n\n```{.r .cell-code}\ndata(\"wage1\", package = \"wooldridge\")\n```\n:::\n\n\n\n\n\n\n## Esercizio 2\n\nConsideriamo i data in `wage2`\n\n\n::: {.cell layout-align=\"center\"}\n\n```{.r .cell-code}\ndata(\"wage2\", package = \"wooldridge\")\n```\n:::\n\n\n\n- $wage$ sono le retribuzioni mensili\n- $educ$ sono gli anni di istruzioni\n- $exper$ anni di experience\n\nStimiamo le seguente regressioni:\n\n\n::: {.cell layout-align=\"center\"}\n\n```{.r .cell-code}\nreg_wage1 <- feols(wage ~ educ + exper + tenure, data = wage2, vcov = \"hetero\")\nreg_logwage1 <- feols(log(wage) ~ educ + exper + tenure, data = wage2, vcov = \"hetero\")\n\nmodelsummary(list(\"Wage\" = reg_wage1, \"Log Wage\" = reg_logwage1), gof_omit = \"AIC|BIC|RMSE|R2 Adj.\")\n```\n\n::: {.cell-output-display}\n\n```{=html}\n<!-- preamble start -->\n\n    <script src=\"https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/gh/vincentarelbundock/tinytable@main/inst/tinytable.js\"></script>\n\n    <script>\n      // Create table-specific functions using external factory\n      const tableFns_34nnsjgyedxaq12x4o7i = TinyTable.createTableFunctions(\"tinytable_34nnsjgyedxaq12x4o7i\");\n      // tinytable span after\n      window.addEventListener('load', function () {\n          var cellsToStyle = [\n            // tinytable style arrays after\n          { positions: [ { i: '10', j: 2 }, { i: '10', j: 3 } ], css_id: 'tinytable_css_d517gxluwm9r499kkp6k',}, \n          { positions: [ { i: '8', j: 2 }, { i: '8', j: 3 } ], css_id: 'tinytable_css_mdsy551cbuaavq6zfabr',}, \n          { positions: [ { i: '1', j: 2 }, { i: '2', j: 2 }, { i: '3', j: 2 }, { i: '4', j: 2 }, { i: '5', j: 2 }, { i: '6', j: 2 }, { i: '7', j: 2 }, { i: '9', j: 2 }, { i: '1', j: 3 }, { i: '2', j: 3 }, { i: '3', j: 3 }, { i: '4', j: 3 }, { i: '5', j: 3 }, { i: '6', j: 3 }, { i: '7', j: 3 }, { i: '9', j: 3 } ], css_id: 'tinytable_css_5k1vp02if6ukypmskpaz',}, \n          { positions: [ { i: '0', j: 2 }, { i: '0', j: 3 } ], css_i